==Production==
The film was part of Taka Ichise's announcement from May 14, 2004 where he announced his help in the creation of Entertainment FARM, which was the first Japanese company to provide financial backing for films. The company operated like an investment firm, focusing exclusively on films.{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=173}}{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=174}} Among their first productions, was [[Takashige Ichise]]'s [[J-Horror Theater]] series, which ''Infection'' was part of.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=434}}<ref name="japantimes" />{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=173}} The series was a list of free-standing horror films directed by [[Masayuki Ochiai]], [[Norio Tsuruta]], [[Takashi Shimizu]], [[Kiyoshi Kurosawa]], [[Hideo Nakata]] and [[Hiroshi Takahashi (screenwriter)|Hiroshi Takahashi]].{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=173}}

Ochiai wrote the screenplay for ''Infection'', which is an adaptation of one of his early scripts for a segment from ''[[Tales of the Unusual]]''.{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=174}} ''Infection'' began production in April 2004.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|title=Lions Gate lines up 'J-Horror'|last=Gardner|first=Chris|date=May 17, 2004|page=13|ISSN=0018-3660|volume=383|issue=46}}</ref>

== Release ==
''Infection'' was released theatrically in Japan on October 2, 2004 where it was distributed by [[Toho]].{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=295}}{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=434}}  The film was released as a double feature with ''[[Premonition (2004 film)|Premonition]]'' in Japan.{{sfn|Kalat|2007|p=295}} In the film's opening week in Japan, it was the second highest film in the box office being only beaten by ''[[I, Robot (film)|I, Robot]]''.<ref name="bom-debut">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/japan/?yr=2004&wk=40&p=.htm|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|title=Japan Box Office: October 2–3, 2004|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref> It grossed a total of $1,320,123 in its first week.<ref name="bom-debut" /> The film grossed a total of $6,609,556 in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fKANSEN01&country=JP&wk=2004W43&id=_fKANSEN01&p=.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|title=Kansen|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>

In the United States, the film was released directly to DVD by [[Lions Gate|Lions Gate Films Home Entertainment]] on May 17, 2005.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=434}}

==Reception==
''[[The Japan Times]]'' stated that ''Infection'' will "look familiar to J Horror fans" and resembled an episodes of ''[[The X-Files]]'' without Scully and Mulder.<ref name="japantimes" /> The review concluded that the director "stresses [[Grand Guignol]] atmospherics more, rational-sounding explanations less. His hospital breathes with a menace, madness and despair so pervasive that only a huge, obliterating explosion could bring escape -- in this life, at least."<ref name="japantimes">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050415095727/http://search.japantimes.co.jp/print/features/film2004/ff20041006a1.htm|url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/print/features/film2004/ff20041006a1.htm|accessdate=April 27, 2016|archivedate=April 15, 2005|last=Schilling|first=Mark|title=Be Doubly Afraid|work=[[The Japan Times]]|date=October 6, 2004}}</ref> David Kalat (''[[Video Watchdog]]'') referred to the film as "a claustrophobic chamber piece" and "an overwhelming sensory experience that employs every cinematic trick in Ochiai's repertoire to establish a tone of intense dread."<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Video Watchdog]]|title=Infection|year=2006|issue=124|page=51|last=Kalat|first=David}}</ref> ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' gave the film a mixed review, opining that "after a fairly engrossing trawl through horror conventions, the film takes a reckless plunge into oneiric ambiguity that fails to provide satisfying closure"<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Sight & Sound]]|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|title=Infection|last=Leyland|first=Matthew|volume=16|issue=12|page=89|date=December 2006|ISSN=0037-4806}}</ref>

