====Faculty====
;{{nihongo|{{va|Shōji Kubodera}}|久保寺紹二|Kubodera Shōji}}
:{{voiced by|[[Kōzō Mito]]|[[David Matranga]]<ref name="ann eng cast"/>}}
:Class 3-3 homeroom teacher.{{gnr|ch|1}} In July, after realizing that the countermeasures to the Class 3-3 calamity are not working, he kills his bedridden mother by smothering her with a pillow the night before [[suicide|stabbing himself]] in the neck in front of the class.{{gnr|ch|11|,|12}}

;{{nihongo|{{va|Tatsuji Chibiki}}|千曳 辰治|Chibiki Tatsuji}}
:{{voiced by|[[Hiroaki Hirata]]<ref name="ann jp cast"/>|[[David Wald]]}}, Yoshihiko Hakamaka (live-action film)
:Reiko describes him as the "ruler" of the secondary library. He typically dresses in all black.{{gnr|ch|3}} He was the teacher for Class 3-3 in 1972, the year Misaki Yomiyama died. Some years later, he resigned as a teacher but stayed on as librarian, claiming that he was "running away [from the curse]" but, staying nearby out of guilt. Since then, he's kept a record of the phenomena, the deceased and their connections; and shares his findings with Kōichi and Mei.{{gnr|ch|10}}

===Others===
;{{nihongo|{{va|Misaki Yomiyama}}|夜見山 岬|Yomiyama Misaki}}
:The honor student from Yomiyama Middle School's Class 3-3 in 1972. He was extremely popular and well-liked by his peers and teacher. He died in a house fire that also claimed the lives of his brother and both his parents.<ref>{{Harvnb|Ayatsuji|2009|p=385}}</ref> His classmates were so heartbroken by his untimely death and could not accept it, that at school they pretended as if he were still alive, which led to a mysterious photo with the supposedly dead Misaki in it.<ref name="book p8-13">{{Harvnb|Ayatsuji|2009|pp=8–13}}</ref>{{gnr|ch|1|,|15}}

;{{nihongo|{{va|Sanae Mizuno}}|水野 沙苗|Mizuno Sanae}}
:{{voiced by|Seiko Yoshida|[[Carli Mosier]]<ref name="ann eng cast"/>}}, [[Hiroko Sato]] (live-action film)
:A nurse at Yūmigaoka Hospital who befriends Koichi. A running gag is that she is [[Accident-proneness|accident-prone]].{{gnr|ch|1|,|2|,|5}} She has a younger brother named Takeru in Class 3-3.{{gnr|ch|4}} She tries to assist Kōichi in unraveling the mystery of Yomiyama North by giving him information she gleans from discussions with her colleagues and her brother.{{gnr|ch|3|,|5}} In June, she is killed when the elevator she was riding breaks its cable and falls down the shaft; the impact causes the ceiling beam to fall on her.{{gnr|ch|6|,|7}}

;{{nihongo|{{va|Katsumi Matsunaga}}|松永 克己|Matsunaga Katsumi}}
:{{voiced by|Shinya Takahashi|[[Illich Guardiola]]}}
:A former Yomiyama North Middle School student from Class 3-3 of 1983, and one of Reiko's classmates. During their summer trip, when he had killed a classmate, he discovers that the other people in the class suddenly have no knowledge of that classmate. He realizes he had killed the Casualty, making this the only known case of the phenomenon stopping halfway through the year.{{gnr|ch|14|,|15}} He recorded his theories and confession on an [[Compact Cassette|audio cassette]] and hid it in the school for future students to find.{{gnr|ch|15}} After graduation, he moved to Tokyo to pursue his studies. He became a banker, but quit after a few years, returning to Yomiyama to help with the family business.{{volume needed|date=August 2015|reason=not listed in the manga, is it described in the novel?}} He is a regular at Inoya Cafė, where Tomoka Inose works.{{gnr|ch|13}}

;{{nihongo|{{va|Tomoka Inose}}|猪瀬 知香|Inose Tomoka}}
:{{voiced by|Mahiro Inoue|[[Maggie Flecknoe]]}}
:Yūya's older half-sister. A waitress at Inoya Cafė, she attended Yomiyama North Middle School during 1983, though she was not part of Class 3-3. Although aware of the rumors about said class, she did not believe them until Yūya, fearing for his life, explained the situation to her. Katsumi Matsunaga is a regular at the cafe where she works.{{gnr|ch|13}}<!--Source doesn't say that Tomoka talks occasionally to Katsumi--><ref>{{Harvnb|Ayatsuji|2009|pp=486–489}}</ref>

;{{nihongo|{{va|Mineko Numata}}|沼田 峯子|Numata Mineko}}
:{{voiced by|[[Rie Takahashi]]|Vicki Barosh}}
:Ikuo Takabayashi's grandmother. A gentle warm-hearted grandmother, though she proved to be an insane crone murderer due to Ikuo's death. In the novel, she is responsible for the murder of Manabu Maejima, Izumi Akazawa, Takako Sugiura, Junta Nakao, Shigeki Yonemura, and her husband Kensaku during the summer trip. She then proceeded to commit suicide by biting off her tongue, making her along with her husband one of the seven "Deaths of August".{{volume needed|date=August 2015|reason=this detail is in the novel? manga?}}  In the anime, she is not directly responsible for Sugiura's or Akazawa's death, and she was killed with a frying pan by Chibiki, saving Yūya Mochizuki and Naoya Teshigawara.

==Media==

===Novels===
''Another'' is a 677-page novel written by [[Yukito Ayatsuji]]. The novel was originally serialized in Kadokawa Shoten's literary magazine ''Yasai Jidai'' in intermittent periods between the August 2006 and May 2009 issues. A compiled ''[[tankōbon]]'' volume was published on October 29, 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/book/bk_detail.php?pcd=200905000546|title=Another|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|accessdate=July 30, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> and a two-volume ''[[bunkobon]]'' edition was released on September 25, 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/bunko/bk_detail.php?pcd=201106000725 | title=Another (上) | publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] | accessdate=November 21, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/bunko/bk_detail.php?pcd=201106000724|title=Another (下)|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|accessdate=November 21, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> A re-release of the ''bunkobon'' edition featuring illustrations by [[Noizi Ito]] was released under the [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]] Sneaker Bunko on March 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/lnovel/bk_detail.php?pcd=201109000161 | title=Another (上) | publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]] | accessdate=March 9, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/lnovel/bk_detail.php?pcd=201109000160|title=Another (下)|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|accessdate=March 9, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref> A spin-off novel titled ''Another: Episode S/0'' was released on July 31, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/book/bk_detail.php?pcd=201205000042|title=Another: Episode S/0|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|accessdate=July 20, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>  It is two novels in one binding. ''Another S'' is a side novel set in the same time period, an adventure of Mei Misaki during summer vacation. ''Another 0'' is set during Aunt Reiko's year in class 3-3, in 1983. A sequel novel with the tentative title ''Another 2'' has been announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-02-28/ayatsuji-plans-2-more-novels-of-horror-franchise-another|title=Ayatsuji Plans 2 More Novels of Horror Franchise 'Another'|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 28, 2012|accessdate=February 28, 2012}}</ref> [[Yen Press]] has licensed the novels in North America.<ref name="yenpress">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-07-13/yen-press-adds-another-horror-novel-and-manga-junya-inoue-btooom-manga|title=Yen Press Adds {{'}}''Another''{{'}} Horror Novel & Manga, Junya Inoue's ''BTOOOM!'' Manga|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 13, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2012}}</ref>

===Manga===
A [[manga]] adaptation illustrated by Hiro Kiyohara was serialized between the May 2010 and January 2012 issues of Kadokawa Shoten's ''[[Young Ace]]'' magazine. Four ''tankōbon'' volumes were released between October 4, 2010 and December 29, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=201005000029|title=Another (1)|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|accessdate=July 30, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kadokawa.co.jp/comic/bk_detail.php?pcd=201105000119|title=Another (4)|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|accessdate=December 5, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> A "0th" volume of the manga was released on May 26, 2012. [[Yen Press]] has licensed the original four-volume manga in North America and released it as an omnibus.<ref name="yenpress" />

===Anime===
{{main|List of Another episodes}}
A 12-episode [[anime]] television series adaptation produced by [[P.A.Works]] and directed by Tsutomu Mizushima<ref name="ANN-0811">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2011-08-27/anime-another-with-noizi-ito-p.a-works-debuts-in-january|title=Anime ''Another'' with Noizi Ito, P.A. Works Debuts in January|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=August 27, 2011}}</ref> aired in Japan between January 10 and March 27, 2012. The screenplay was written by Ryō Higaki, and the chief animation director Yuriko Ishii based the character design used in the anime on Noizi Ito's original concept art.<ref name="ANN-0811"/><ref name="official-about">{{cite web|url=http://www.another-anime.jp/about/|title=Staff & Cast|publisher=[[P.A.Works]]|accessdate=November 21, 2011|language=Japanese}}</ref> The music was produced by [[Kow Otani]], and the sound director is Yoshikazu Iwanami.<ref name="official-about"/> The anime has two theme songs: the opening theme {{Nihongo|"Kyōmu Densen"|凶夢伝染||"Nightmare Contagion"}} by the band [[Ali Project]], and the ending theme "Anamnesis" by [[Annabel (Japanese singer)|Annabel]]. [[Section23 Films#Sentai Filmworks|Sentai Filmworks]] licensed the series in North America, releasing it on BD/DVD on July 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-01-16/sentai-filmworks-licenses-horror-tv-anime-another|title=Sentai Filmworks Licenses Horror TV Anime ''Another''|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 16, 2012|accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> An [[original video animation]] (OVA) episode set before the beginning of the series was released on May 26, 2012 with a "0th" volume of the manga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-03-02/promo-for-episode-0-of-horror-anime-another-streamed|title=Promo for Episode 0 of Horror Anime 'Another' Streamed|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 2, 2012|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref> [[MVM Films]] released the series, including the OVA, in the United Kingdom and Ireland in late 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-03-20/mvm-to-release-another-on-blu-ray-and-dvd|title=MVM to Release Another on Blu-ray and DVD|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref>

===Live-action film===
{{main|Another (film)}}
A live-action film adaptation [[Another (film)|of the same name]], directed by Takeshi Furusawa<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2011-02-15/ring-horror-films-sadako-gets-3d-live-action-film |title=Ring Horror Films' Sadako Gets 3D Live-Action Film |date=February 15, 2011 |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=February 16, 2011}}</ref> and produced by [[Kadokawa Pictures]] was released in Japanese theaters on August 4, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2012-03-02/live-action-film-teaser-of-horror-novel-another-posted|title=Live-Action Film Teaser of Horror Novel 'Another' Posted|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 2, 2012|accessdate=March 2, 2012}}</ref> The theme song is {{Nihongo|"Rakuen"|楽園||"Paradise"}} by [[Miliyah Kato]].

==Reception==
{{incomplete|section|date=April 2012}}
The novel ranked third in both the ''[[Honkaku Mystery Best 10#2010|2010 Honkaku Mystery Best 10]]'' and the ''[[Kono Mystery ga Sugoi!#2010|Kono Mystery ga Sugoi! 2010]]'' mystery fiction guide books. It was nominated for the 2010 [[Honkaku Mystery Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://honkaku.com/english.html|title= The Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|publisher=Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>

